Write the complex number 
\begin_inset Formula $z=3-3\I$
\end_inset

 in polar form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
First,
 we normalize:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs z=\sqrt{3^{2}+3^{2}}=3\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

,
 so we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{z}{\abs z}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\I$
\end_inset

.
 This corresponds to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}})$
\end_inset

 on the unit circle,
 which corresponds to the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $z=3\sqrt{2}\e^{-\I\frac{\pi}{4}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

