\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
7.5.11
\end_layout

\end_inset

Express the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\lambda)=\lambda^{3}-3\lambda^{2}+7\lambda-5$
\end_inset

 as a product of linear factors over 
\begin_inset Formula $\C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
We start by guessing a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 We try calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $f(1)=1-3+7-5=0$
\end_inset

.
 Great,
 we got in on the first guess!
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\lambda)=(\lambda-1)(a\lambda^{2}+b\lambda+c)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
We find 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=5$
\end_inset

 by looking at the constant and cubic term.
 If we look at the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 term,
 we get the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $7=-b+c$
\end_inset

,
 leading to 
\begin_inset Formula $b=-2$
\end_inset

,
 and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\lambda)=(\lambda-1)(\lambda^{2}-2\lambda+5).
\]

\end_inset

Now we factor the quadratic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{2}-2\lambda+5$
\end_inset

.
 The roots may be found by the quadratic formula:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\pm}=\frac{2\pm\sqrt{4-4\cdot5}}{2}=1\pm2\I.
\]

\end_inset

This leads to the factorization
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\lambda)=(\lambda-1)(\lambda-1-2\I)(\lambda-1+2\I).
\]

\end_inset

This completes the solution.
\end_layout

